# Standards — OrderFlow API

## Code That Looks Fine But Isn't

```ruby
# RACE CONDITION — two users reserve the last copy simultaneously
book = Book.find(params[:book_id])
if book.copies_available > 0
  book.update!(copies_available: book.copies_available - 1)
  Reservation.create!(book: book, user: current_user)
end
# Both threads read copies_available = 1, both decrement, copies_available = -1
# Fix: wrap in transaction with Book.lock.find
```

```ruby
# DUPLICATE CHECK RACE — application-level uniqueness isn't enough
if Reservation.where(user: user, book: book, status: [:pending, :active]).exists?
  render_error("duplicate")
else
  Reservation.create!(user: user, book: book, status: :pending)
end
# Two requests pass the exists? check before either inserts
# Fix: partial unique index in the migration: WHERE status IN ('pending', 'active')
```

```ruby
# CANCEL RACE — checking status outside the lock
def cancel(reservation)
  return error if reservation.status == "cancelled"  # reads stale data
  ActiveRecord::Base.transaction do
    reservation.update!(status: "cancelled")          # no lock, no re-check
    book.update!(copies_available: book.copies_available + 1)
  end
end
# Two concurrent cancels both pass the status check, both increment
# Fix: lock the reservation inside the transaction, re-read status
```

```ruby
# N+1 — invisible until production load
def index
  @orders = user.orders
  render json: @orders.map { |o| { id: o.id, item: o.item.name } }
end
# 1 query for orders + N queries for items. Fine with 5 orders, death with 5000.
# Fix: user.orders.includes(:item)
```

```ruby
# TABLE LOCK — adding a column with a default on a large table
class AddStatusToOrders < ActiveRecord::Migration[7.1]
  def change
    add_column :orders, :priority, :integer, default: 0
  end
end
# Locks the orders table for the entire rewrite. 10M rows = minutes of downtime.
# Fix: add_column without default, backfill separately, then set default
```

```ruby
# INCONSISTENT ERRORS — three endpoints, three formats
# Endpoint 1: { error: "not found" }
# Endpoint 2: { message: "Invalid", errors: [...] }
# Endpoint 3: { status: 422, detail: "bad request" }
# Mobile team writes three different error handlers
# Fix: one envelope everywhere: { error: { code: String, message: String } }
```

## When to Go Deeper

When writing or reviewing a migration, read `.claude/references/rails-patterns.md` — especially safe migration patterns and lock-duration checks.
When designing or reviewing an endpoint, read `.claude/references/rails-patterns.md` — especially N+1 prevention and pagination requirements.
When reviewing existing controller code, read `.claude/references/rails-patterns.md` — check for N+1 queries, missing pagination, and thin-controller violations.
When deploying or preparing for production, read `.claude/references/rails-patterns.md` — verify migration safety, index strategy, and CI status before shipping.
When diagnosing slow tests, read `.claude/references/rails-patterns.md` — check factory design, unnecessary database hits, and spec isolation patterns.
When scoping a new feature or system, read `.claude/references/rails-patterns.md` — audit existing code for violations first, then plan migrations, endpoints, and specs using established patterns.
